{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492870","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492870"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:48:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:48:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1174"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1174"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.1,0.1,0.01,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108958"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1174","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1174"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1174"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91328"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"656"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4974"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11633"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1336"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2428"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34323"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39078"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42235"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/108958"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 27-year-old man is brought into the Emergency Department after being involved in a motorbike crash two hours ago and injuring his left leg. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn initial resuscitation is performed based on the Advanced Trauma Life Support protocol to control active bleeding and maintain blood pressure, and he is currently haemodynamically stable. A further repeated detailed assessment of the limb injury is performed. On examination, there is a 7 cm long open wound over the shin with clear deformity and angulation of the lower limb and a fragment of tibia visible. The fracture is reduced in the Emergency Department however the foot remains cool and pedal pulses are diminished.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Plain X-ray","CT angiogram","Intravenous antibiotics","Apply sterile dressing","Immediate surgical referral"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate surgical referral\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step. This patient has an open tibial fracture with hard signs of vascular compromise (cool foot, diminished pulses) despite initial reduction and stabilisation. Immediate surgical review is required to assess for possible vascular repair and limb salvage. Delaying for further imaging or other interventions risks irreversible ischaemia and limb loss.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPlain X-ray\u003C/strong\u003E is important for fracture assessment but should not delay urgent surgical intervention when there are signs of vascular compromise. Imaging can be performed after surgical review if time permits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E may be useful in stable patients without hard signs of vascular injury, but in this scenario, clinical findings are sufficient to warrant immediate operative management. Imaging should not delay transfer to theatre. Even if angiography is to be considered, the first step must be to contact the surgical team.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are essential in open fractures to reduce infection risk, but in the context of vascular compromise, restoring perfusion takes priority. Antibiotics can be administered en route to theatre or intra-operatively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EApply sterile dressing\u003C/strong\u003E is an important part of initial wound care for open fractures, but it does not address the urgent need for vascular assessment and intervention. Dressing the wound should not delay immediate surgical involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOpen fractures with vascular injury are limb-threatening emergencies. Early recognition and prompt surgical intervention are critical to optimise outcomes and prevent permanent disability or amputation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Open fractures with vascular compromise require immediate surgical intervention to prevent limb loss.","Delaying definitive management for imaging or antibiotics in patients with open fractures with vascular compromise can increase ischaemia time and worsen outcomes."],"references":["Melvin JS, Dombroski DG, Torbert JT, et al. Open tibial shaft fractures: I. Evaluation and initial wound management. J Am Acad Orthop Surg 2010; 18:10. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20044487/","American College of Surgeons Committee on Trauma. Advanced Trauma Life Support (ATLS) Student Course Manual, 9th ed, American College of Surgeons, Chicago 2012.","Fox N, Rajani RR, Bokhari F, et al. Evaluation and management of penetrating lower extremity arterial trauma: an Eastern Association for the Surgery of Trauma practice management guideline. J Trauma Acute Care Surg 2012; 73:S315. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/23114487/","Orthopaedic Trauma Association: Open Fracture Study Group. A new classification scheme for open fractures. J Orthop Trauma 2010; 24:457. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/20657245/","Scalea TM, DuBose J, Moore EE, et al. Western Trauma Association critical decisions in trauma: management of the mangled extremity. J Trauma Acute Care Surg 2012; 72:86. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/22310120/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91328"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1174"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91328","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91328"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-15T10:58:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-15T10:59:46+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1174"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"108958"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"78","lin